[2]
Date: Mon 17 May 2004 9:58 AM
From: Susan E Shaw, Companion Animals <Susan.E.Shaw@bristol.ac.uk>


I was slightly bemused by the comments in this article regarding veterinary
surgeons sending most samples to "Tropical Health schools". The laboratory
which is mentioned in the article is based in such a place, although run
via University of Liverpool Veterinary School. Most veterinary surgeons are
referring samples for companion animal exotic diseases to commercial
private veterinary laboratories, to labs at veterinary schools, and to the
Veterinary Laboratories Agency (Government agency doing export testing for
dogs and cats). They need advice on treatment and management of these
diseases as well.

We have had a dedicated polymerase chain reaction (PCR) diagnostic service
for multiple pathogens of companion animals "exotic" to the UK based at the
University of Bristol Veterinary School for the past 4 years. The current
sample submissions to our lab alone are more 10 times those mentioned for
the lab in the article. We do pass on _Leishmania_ serology where necessary
to the laboratory mentioned in the article.

There is no doubt that the number of dogs traveling into the UK with exotic
infectious diseases is increasing rapidly. Those of us with experience in
the area are not surprised, as there was minimal interest in prevention of
diseases other than rabies and _E. multilocularis_ from the government. In
addition, companion animal travel was actively encouraged with a public
relations campaign by DEFRA (Department of Environment Food and Rural
Affairs) for the first few years until the backlash of animals dying after
return occurred.

However, many veterinary practices are still not aware of the risks of
serious canine diseases and are not advising routine preventative measures
for animals travelling into endemic areas. UK dogs are immunologically
naive, and sudden exposure to _Babesia_, in particular, has resulted in
peracute disease far more serious clinically than is seen in France where
most of them contract infection.

DEFRA have now set up a voluntary recording scheme for exotic disease cases
in travelling small animals and will be releasing an analysis of the first
years results very soon. I have seen these results, and although they
represent only a proportion of animals actually contracting disease, the
trend seen is the same as in our lab.

--
Susan Shaw
School of Veterinary Medicine,
Bristol University, UK
<susan.e.shaw@Bristol.ac.uk>

[Following Susan's advice, I navigated the DEFRA website and came upon this
6 month report (March-August 2003) on illnesses in companion animals that
had traveled on the continent or had been living there. - Mod.MHJ]

