[3]
Date: 18 May 2004
From: ProMED-mail<promed@promedmail.org>
Source: DACTARI - Dog and Cat Travel And Risk Information for pet owners
[edited]
<http://www.defra.gov.uk/animalh/quarantine/pets/dactari.htm>


DACTARI - 6 month report
------------------------
This report updates information which was provided in a letter to the
Veterinary Record 16 Aug 2003 Volume 153, Number 7. The first 6 months...

On 1 Mar 2003 Defra launched DACTARI (Dog and Cat Travel and Risk
Information). This scheme was to find out about the occurrence of exotic
diseases in dogs and cats in Great Britain. DACTARI is a national voluntary
reporting scheme for the investigation of the possible occurrence of exotic
diseases of dogs and cats in England, Wales and Scotland.

In the first 6 months of the scheme [Mar through Aug 2003] 13 reports of
exotic disease in dogs were reported from England and Wales. There were
none for cats. All 12 cases were of dogs with a history of travel or
residency abroad. Of these, 9 entered (or re-entered) Great Britain through
the Pet Travel Scheme and 4 entered via quarantine.

Diagnoses reported
13 reports were received for cases which were diagnosed during 2003. One
dog was diagnosed with 2 exotic diseases, so there were a total of 14
diagnoses. Of the 14 diagnoses only 2 were based on clinical signs alone.
The remainder were confirmed on the basis of both clinical findings and
laboratory tests.

The majority (6) of the diagnoses were for leishmaniasis, with 4 confirmed
cases and 2 suspected. Others were of babesiosis (5) and ehrlichiosis (3).
[Maps showing where these cases lived in the UK are on the website. There
is no information on where the cases might have become infected.]

3 reports were received for cases which occurred prior to 2003. 2 were of
leishmaniasis and one of babesiosis; the former were reported from England,
the latter from Scotland.

[Then follows pet-health advice to owners and to veterinarians on how to
report cases.]

--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[This is like other reports that lack denominators; the numerators are hard
to judge without knowing either the number of animals accompanying their
owners on holidays, and for incidence density the number of dog days of
risk, for example. Also while the DACTARI effort is admirable, it is a
passive system and therefore will by its nature underreport case numbers,
with probably a bias towards the more lethal incidents, while ignoring the
minor illnesses; vide the Telegraph claim of 300 cases in 2003 and DEFRA's
reported figure of 13. The truth? Who knows? It would be helpful if some
sentinel practices were recruited to provide structured reports on all
their clients' travel experiences -- good, bad, and indifferent. Also these
sentinel animals and others would provide a good cheap resource for
archived agents and their genomic characterisation, as a baseline of such
data is always useful. If matched with a similar organisation in France,
Spain or Italy, it would be possible to compare virulences of these
pathogens in domestic and visiting animals. When the Exotic Diseases
Division, DEFRA, publishes its 12 month report, we will be glad to help
them disseminate their results. - Mod.MHJ]
